1
00:00:04,815 --> 00:00:07,273
You’ll hear people commonly say,
they’ll go …

2
00:00:07,288 --> 00:00:12,184
Some uncle or auntie
meeting someone who’s younger,

3
00:00:12,184 --> 00:00:14,480
they say as someone’s growing up,

4
00:00:17,370 --> 00:00:19,287
or even parents will say it,

5
00:00:19,287 --> 00:00:23,277
“I remember when you were just
a twinkle in your father’s eye.”

6
00:00:23,564 --> 00:00:27,379
[A Twinkle in the Eye of Viṣṇu]

7
00:00:27,379 --> 00:00:28,238
That’s the expression.

8
00:00:28,238 --> 00:00:30,825
I don’t know
how well it translates,

9
00:00:30,825 --> 00:00:32,552
but they say that.

10
00:00:32,552 --> 00:00:36,626
And this I find very interesting
because we’re saying,

11
00:00:36,626 --> 00:00:39,732
“Mahāviṣṇu glanced”,

12
00:00:40,317 --> 00:00:43,220
like, “A twinkle in Mahāviṣṇu’s eye”,

13
00:00:43,220 --> 00:00:45,277
if you want to say.

14
00:00:47,215 --> 00:00:50,872
We understand this intuitively

15
00:00:50,872 --> 00:00:53,508
without getting too clinical about it.

16
00:00:53,508 --> 00:00:56,782
Where is the origin of all of us?

17
00:00:56,782 --> 00:01:00,135
Within the twinkle of an eye

18
00:01:00,504 --> 00:01:03,940
between a mother and a father!

19
00:01:04,340 --> 00:01:07,024
They looked at each other

20
00:01:07,024 --> 00:01:10,627
and then there was 
impregnation and birth.

21
00:01:10,627 --> 00:01:14,326
[Laughing]

22
00:01:14,326 --> 00:01:16,484
How perfect is that?

23
00:01:16,484 --> 00:01:19,964
It’s right in the Brahma-saṁhitā, 
saying the same thing:

24
00:01:19,964 --> 00:01:23,785
Viṣṇu looked at Māyā, 
one thing led to another,

25
00:01:23,785 --> 00:01:26,516
and all these living beings 
were born.

26
00:01:26,516 --> 00:01:30,589
But rather than that we’ll think …

27
00:01:30,912 --> 00:01:34,486
What’s the word? … Disparagingly, 
towards Mahāviṣṇu,

28
00:01:34,486 --> 00:01:37,268
we’ll say, “His eyes are half-closed,
lying in yoga-nidrā,

29
00:01:37,268 --> 00:01:40,449
the glance personifies
the Śambhu …”

30
00:01:40,449 --> 00:01:45,634
See, Śiva, he’s the one 
who can do all of this interim

31
00:01:45,634 --> 00:01:47,309
intermediate work

32
00:01:47,309 --> 00:01:50,293
between the spiritual world 
and the material.

33
00:01:50,293 --> 00:01:53,439
Śiva is in that unique position,

34
00:01:53,439 --> 00:01:56,269
and sometimes has to do things

35
00:01:56,269 --> 00:01:59,857
that he expresses 
he’s not entirely happy about.

36
00:01:59,857 --> 00:02:03,802
Like when he preaches 
māyāvād philosophy

37
00:02:03,802 --> 00:02:07,481
as Śaṅkar Āchārya,

38
00:02:07,481 --> 00:02:09,197
and is deluding people.

39
00:02:09,197 --> 00:02:13,729
[He says,] “What kind of service is this?
My job is to delude people?”

40
00:02:13,729 --> 00:02:15,709
[Laughing]

41
00:02:15,949 --> 00:02:20,582
So, sometimes 
Śrīla Guru Mahārāj would say—

42
00:02:20,582 --> 00:02:26,614
one of the things he is often noted for
is his spiritual common sense, so—

43
00:02:28,504 --> 00:02:33,304
if you faithfully
hear these descriptions,

44
00:02:33,811 --> 00:02:36,688
you’ll see at a certain point,

45
00:02:36,688 --> 00:02:41,119
what sounded very mystical,
abstract, inconceivable,

46
00:02:41,134 --> 00:02:46,371
starts mirroring common sense.

47
00:02:46,386 --> 00:02:51,794
And that makes it all
the more believable,

48
00:02:53,101 --> 00:02:56,926
accessible, and charming.

49
00:02:57,423 --> 00:03:01,247
The glance of Mahāviṣṇu!

50
00:03:02,172 --> 00:03:06,231
And we say, “Oh, like in this world,
it starts with the glance”.

51
00:03:06,231 --> 00:03:09,658
How beautiful, it’s poetic even.

